    {
      "id": "ddf7e7798d693c2e362f35d3c0acb4eb72536f77",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2014-09-05 00:24:00.000000000",
      "message": "Change has been successfully cherry-picked as 555eb580e547fb263faee0a4d88482789171211b",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "96a408f865ef4af00fadd01c7332135dd2c0af1c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2014-09-05 10:31:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nI'm reluctant to the special flags for very special cases.. I think in general it makes sense do not hold a reference to the child objects for long (in contrast to what we do now) - so OSP objects aren't consuming memory.\n\n(2) and (3) if an object isn't referenced for long, then this shouldn't be a problem\n\nadding special flags can be easier in short term, but in long term it tends to lead to additional issues.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "e4b73a31d5295388ccee521a0c9a06de7a295a59",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-09-09 00:08:54.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nAlex: Most of the LFSCK check/repair are async operations, for example, we do not know how long the the async getattr from the OST will take (depends on the network connection and the MDS/OSS workload). On the other hand, for a widely striped object, it may take long time for the assistant thread to verifying all the stripes (while related objects references holding). So it is NOT a rare case of holding object's reference for some a bit long time under current LFSCK use cases. If it is proved to be a bad model and has to be changed, we can do that in the LFSCK phase IV.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "c33175400391c808c8640d03733b9a6043740613",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2014-09-09 05:35:19.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nwell, \"longer\" doesn't mean a deadlock, right?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "5d4791e0e4ff70f43b1d63634112103324271c30",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-09-09 05:47:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nYes, if we allow the relationship between the child object and its parent object to be detached anytime, then even though the parent object will be held for very long time, then it still will not cause deadlock directly, but the condition is we are sure such detachment will not cause some unknown races. From my view, currently using a special flag is more safe. I am not mind to consider your way to optimise the LFSCK code in phase IV.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "3e31054a816122713923b62793e859a8b74e137a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-09-09 14:58:24.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nFan Yong, please file a Jira ticket for LFSCK Phase 4 with details and a link to this patch, so this is not forgotten.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "f17bf098c8918398d86801c66bcfc245118cb6d0",
      "author": {
